  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA209-kiḷavi">1. itu kuṟai maṟukkappaṭṭup piṉṉiṉṟa talaimakaṉ āṟṟāṉāy neñciṟkuc colluvāṉāyc colliyatu. 2. tōḻi kēṭṭuk kuṟai muṭippatu payaṉ.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">1. This is what HE said who stood behind [the confidante] after [his] request had been refused, being one who speaks to [his] heart when being unable to bear it. 2. The gist is that the request would be accomplished when the confidante has heard [him].</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA209">
<l>            malaiyiṭam paṭuttuk kōṭṭiya kollait</l>
<l>            taḷipatam peṟṟa kāṉuḻu kuṟavar</l>
<l>            cilavit takala viṭṭuṭaṉ palaviḷain</l>
<l>            tiṟaṅkukural piṟaṅkiya vēṉa luḷḷāṇ</l>
<l>            maḻalaiyaṅ kuṟumakaṇ miḻalaiyan tīṅkural </l>
<l>            kiḷiyun tāmaṟi pavvē yemakkē</l>
<l>            paṭuṅkāṟ paiyu ṭīrum paṭātu</l>
<l>            taviruṅ kālai yāyiṉeṉ</l>
<l>            ṉuyirō ṭellā muṭaṉvāṅ kummē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">            
    <choice>
    <seg>She who doesn’t remember the millet</seg>
    <seg>She is in the millet [field]<note place="foot">T.V.G. insists on taking <term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷāḷ</term> here not in the usual way as neg. f.sg. of <term xml:lang="ta">uḷ</term> "to remember", but as f.sg. of <term xml:lang="ta">uḷ</term> "to be". In that case, actually, we would expect <term xml:lang="ta">uḷaḷ</term> or at the utmost <term xml:lang="ta">uḷāḷ</term>. T.V.G. argues by content: she must be in the field for the rest to make sense. However, to me it seems possible to imagine a situation where HE waits for HER to take up her usual work in the fields, but she does not come.</note></seg>
    </choice>
    that glistened,</l>
<l rend="indent">ears coming down,</l>
<l rend="indent2">many ripening, after few seeds had been scattered<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">akala viṭṭu-uṭaṉ</term>: literally "along with having widely let go of a few seeds". It seems <term xml:lang="ta">uṭaṉ</term> with the absolutive gives an almost conjunction-like flavour of concomitance.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">by the forest-ploughing hill people when the clearing had</l>
<l rend="indent">obtained the right state of wetness, brought under control [and]</l>
<l rend="indent3">fenced(?)<note place="foot">Thus T.V.G.’s interpretation of <term xml:lang="ta">iṭampaṭuttu kōṭṭiya</term>, and it makes sense and sounds quite plausible.</note> in the mountain,</l>
<l>– the parakeets themselves know</l>
<l rend="indent2">the prattling sweet voice of the prattling little woman.</l>
<l rend="indent4">For us,</l>
<l rend="indent">the time it comes to [my ear] sorrow ends,</l>
<l rend="indent2">if there is a time it refrains from coming,</l>
<l>along with my life it will drag away all.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
